Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop a #deep saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting lid) on medium heat. Melt in the @butter{20%g} (see pantry for amount).

When the butter has melted, add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{1%min}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} until coated, ~{1%min}.

Add @salt{1/4%tsp} and the @water{300%ml} for the rice (see pantry for amount) and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%mins}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%mins} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} to the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%mins}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Once the chicken is browned, add the @tikka masala paste{75%g}, @tomato puree{30%g} and @tandoori masala mix{1%sachet} to the chicken. Cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%mins}.

When fragrant, stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @water{150%ml} for the curry (see pantry for both amounts).

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce has thickened, ~{4-5%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once thickened, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

Remove the pan from the heat, then stir through the @creme fraiche{75%g} until combined.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Fluff up the garlic butter rice with a #fork{}, then share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the tandoori style chicken curry.

Enjoy!